notesStmt.note: This is an Ottoman illustrated and illuminated copy of the Tuḥfet ül-aḫyār, which is an Ottoman Turkish version of the well-known story of Sindbad (Sindbādnāmah), written by ʿAbdülkerīm bin Muḥammed during the reign of Sultan Süleyman (Soliman) (reg. 926 AH / 1520 CE -- 974 AH / 1566 CE). The text is written in black naskh script with incidentals in gold and red, and chapter headings are in gold. The manuscript dates to the tenth century AH / sixteenth CE and opens with an illuminated incipit page (fol. 1b). There are a total of six illustrations.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Turkish, Ottoman (1500-1928). The secondary language of this manuscript is Persian.

msItem.note: Text contains words and phrases in Arabic and Persian: Persian equivalents to the Arabic given between the lines in red; Turkish meanings written in margins

layoutDesc.layout: Framing lines in red, black, and blue

handDesc.handNote: Written in small naskh script in black ink with some words in gold and red; chapter headings in gold

decoDesc.decoNote: Six illustrations; illuminated incipit page (fol. 1b) containing a headpiece and the doxological formula (basmalah); illuminated text markers

decoNote.title: Illuminated incipit with headpiece
decoNote.note: This illuminated incipit page has a headpiece inscribed with the doxological formula (basmalah) in white tawqīʿ script on gold background.

decoNote.title: Sindbād instructing the king's son
decoNote.note: The inscription in the panel over the door on the right reads: yā Fattāḥ (oh, Opener).

decoNote.title: One of the king's wives attempting to seduce the prince
decoNote.note: The inscription in the panel on the right reads: al-sulṭān al-ʿādil (the just ruler).

decoNote.title: A meeting between the viziers and the king
decoNote.note: Seven court officials (viziers) plead with the king for the release of the prince due to false accusations made by a woman.

decoNote.title: Confectioner directing a parrot to watch his unfaithful wife
decoNote.note: A confectioner is shown directing a parrot to keep watch over his unfaithful wife. The inscription above the door reads: al-sulṭān (the ruler).

decoNote.title: Prince hunting with his father's ministers
Old woman convincing a young woman by means of a crying dog
